This research investigated a new process that allows the selective sintering of powders. The process, current-activated tip-based sintering (CATS) uses a conducting tip to selectively apply electric current to powders and activate the sintering process. The tip can be stationary or moving, and its control can allow the sintering of simple or complex shapes.  

Based on our work, the following conclusions can be drawn:
1.Two micro-scale Current Activated Tip-based Sintering machines with different precision scales to enable CATS performance using different tip size ranges (&gt;50 micron tip size and 1-50 micron tip size) have been successfully manufactured for micro-scale sintering.
2. We have for the first time localized the spark plasma sintering process using our CATS configuration, with major implications for rapid prototyping. 
3. For macro-scale CATS, an increase in current density and number of duty cycles have been found to increase the sintered density within a well defined process zone beneath the tip, which correspondingly increase the micro-hardness. 
4. Work has also been conducted on micro-scale sintering using the micro-scale CATS machine constructed in this project. Rapid sintering is achieved. 
5.Using a different CNC (of low precision) platform we have been successful at rapid sintering under a moving tip, which has major implications for micro-scale and nano-scale manufacturing. 
6. Finite element modeling work has simulated the macro-scale process zone geometry. The modeling efforts so far has shown the significance of powder compact resistivity and thermal conductivity in localizing the process zone. The modeling demonstrated that the energy required for sintering is significantly less that experimental observed due to loss from contact resistance which has been shown to be substantial. However we believe contact resistance between the tip and the material may play a major contributing role in the heat and electrical energy generation/transfer during the process, and is the subject of current investigation.
7. It is possible to generate more complex shapes by changing the tip design, micro-part removal would however need the use of compacts with low green density.
8. Tip pressure was found to influence localization, material hardness and grain size of the locally sintered region. 
9. For Ni-Ti materials, electric current was found to rapidly cause crystallization of amorphous powders. The amount of Ti2Ni/Ti4Ni2Ox phase was found to vary with cumulative exposure time, it also significantly affected the resulting properties of the sintered regions.
10. There is clear evidence of process zone evolution during CATS processing, a mechanism was suggested to explain the observations. 
11. It was possible for the first time to locally activate (using the high Joule heating capability of CATS) an exothermic reaction between nickel and aluminum powder giving rise to the spontaneous exothermic formation of a nickel-based intermetalic compound. 
